Neural networks are a type of model that mimics the way the human brain learns.
They are great for non-linear and complex relationships, but at its core it is very
similar to linear regression (predicting a straight line with a simple weight and bias).
Because a key idea behind machine learning and artifical intelligence is making
predictions and correcting these predictions, neural networks and their structure
allow for this ability to adapt, and adjust these weights and biases quickly.
These networks are made of neurons. Neurons are made of multiple steps
shown below. These neurons are stored in layers, called the hidden layers, where
each layers is dedicated to a specific task or learning a specific characteristic.
Note that this specific task or characerstic is not explicitly defined, but instead
A neuron receives an input. This is going to be the

OF THE MODEL, AND A THE LOSS GRAPHED AT THE COMBINATION OF THESE
PARAMATERS. WE ARE GOING TO USE GRADIENTS. In summary, the gradient is a
directional guide used in NN TO mavigate the loss landscape of a neural network
towards the minimum of the loss function.
High-Dimensional Space: Imagine if your neural network has, say, 100 parameters (weights and biases combined). This means the loss
landscape exists in a 101-dimensional space. Each point in this space represents a specific configuration of all your network's parameters.
Interaction of Parameters: The value (height) at each point in this space is the loss value for that specific configuration of parameters.
If you change one weight, you move along one dimension in this space. Changing another weight moves you along a different dimension.
Peaks and Valleys: A valley (or a low point) in this landscape represents a set of parameters where the network has lower loss, meaning
better performance. Conversely, a peak (or a high point) represents a set of parameters where the network performs poorly.

A convolutionary layer is composed of filters. These filters
are small matrices that move across the input image
(or the output of the previous layer) pixel by pixel.
Each filter can detect specific features like edges, textures
and complex parts of image, and are learned during
training. Each filter contains a matrix of that filter
size containing the weights. Each successive convolutional
layer tends to capture increasingly complex features compared
to the previous layer, but rememember we might
be worse at validating data at a certain point. start at
a larger filter size and move down!
